Looking at these two sets of numbers:

**Q1: {178, 200, 146, 174, 124, 166, 132, 134, 140, 182}**

This set consists entirely of **even numbers** (all divisible by 2). The numbers range from 124 to 200, with a mean of 153.6. All numbers are composite (non-prime), and they appear to be somewhat clustered around the 130-180 range.

**Q2: {103, 101, 197, 151, 127, 137, 179, 199, 191, 109}**

This set consists entirely of **prime numbers**. All ten numbers are prime, ranging from 101 to 199. This is quite notable - having an unordered set of 10 consecutive integers where every single one happens to be prime is extremely rare and statistically unlikely to occur by chance.

The contrast between the sets is striking: one contains only even composite numbers, the other contains only odd prime numbers. This seems like it might be intentional rather than random selection. [end of text]


